node.text:
🌟 WEBB INTERN SPOTLIGHT: Meet Joanna Pullen 🌟 

"My name is Joanna and I am a NASA Education Intern on the Webb team. Last year I graduated with a Masters in Education from @coloradostateuniversity and began my first year as a Science Educator. I also have my degree in Meteorology from @unc_colorado.

I applied to NASA internships over many years, never being accepted, but due to my determination to be a part of NASA’s amazing work, I remained motivated and was chosen as an intern this summer in my most recent application. I like to share this when talking about my journey, because it is not always a straightforward path into NASA. I want people to know that if you do not get chosen, do not give up – look at it as an opportunity for growth.

My favorite thing about the projects I am working on is that they give me new perspectives into the field of education, which ultimately will make me a stronger educator. This experience has only further inspired me to remain in the field of STEM education. My ultimate career goal is to work as a formal or informal education and outreach specialist at NASA. Outside of work my hobbies include traveling, crafting, snowboarding, hiking, camping, and playing with my dog, Toby, who doubles as my work from home buddy."

Happy Friday! Time to share some Webb-inspired art!
🎨
Slide here to enjoy artwork by:  1) Yvette Cendes (cross-stitch) 2) Jabebo Studio (earrings made of laser cut cereal box paperboard) 3) Derek Mohr (digital logo) 4) Minto Marsh (illustration) 5) Chloe McCance (baked goods) 6) Luke Heberlein (ink and watercolor)
🎨
More information about each piece can be found in our web gallery. (http://jwst.nasa.gov/jwstart) Want to participate? Tag your original art, inspired by the James #Webb Space Telescope, on Twitter or Instagram with @NASAWebb or #JWSTArt, or email us at gsfc-nasawebb@mail.nasa.gov. For more info and rules, see: http://nasa.gov/jwstart
🎨
The James Webb Space Telescope – #NASA’s next infrared space observatory – will not only change what we know, but also how we think about the night sky and our place in the cosmos. This epic mission to look back in time at the first stars and galaxies has inspired artists from around the world to create art inspired by the mission. #spaceart #sciart  #STEAM #NASAWebb

node.text:
What exactly is this ray of blue light?

This is the side of Beta Pictoris, a solar system that is far dustier and younger than ours — and lies only 63 light-years away.

Though this system has been studied since the 1980s, the James Webb Space Telescope presents an amazing opportunity: It can see through the dust and deliver high resolution details that will help researchers model what’s moving around in this system. The result will be a greater understanding of its comets, asteroids, rocks of all sizes, and plenty of dust.

Read more at the link in our bio!
Credits: NASA, ESA, and D. Apai and G. Schneider (University of Arizona)

#NASAWebb #SolarSystem #JWST #JamesWebbSpaceTelescope

node.text:
Three more testing milestones have been completed for #NASAWebb! ✅✅✅
 
The world’s most complex and powerful space telescope is making significant progress in preparations for its launch and upcoming million mile journey.

1. The tower is a pipe structure that helps Webb maintain operating temperatures by separating its cold optics from its warm spacecraft bus. Fully extended, the tower reaches 10 ft in length! Recently tested for the last time, it is now lowered & locked into place for launch.

2.  Here, @BallAerospace technician Larkin Carey carefully removes Webb’s "lens cap,” or Aft Optics Subsystem (AOS) cover, which has kept the observatory’s sensitive instruments clean, contaminant-free, and protected from stray light throughout the integration and test process. With launch approaching, removing this cover is a key step in readying the observatory, and gives engineers the freedom to continue packing up the rest of the observatory into its flight-like formation.
 
“While removing the cover I thought, I’m the last person on Earth that will touch the front of the AOS or ever see the instruments again…after working on Webb for 17 years, it was more emotional of an experience than I expected it to be,” said Carey.

3. Webb’s tennis court-sized sunshield is supported by its pallet structures. Now that Webb’s lens cap has been removed, engineers were able to finish the process of folding these pallets up into their final configuration for launch. Here, the pallets can be seen partially lifted, but have since been fully raised and locked into place for launch. 

Read more at the link in our bio!

Image Credits: NASA/Chris Gunn

node.text:
Recognize this object? The Great Nebula in Orion shines in a different light—infrared—in this photo combining data from the Spitzer and Hershel space telescopes.

Here warmer dust is shown in blue, while cooler dust is green and red. Red dots are young stars within dusty cocoons. The powerful infrared instruments of #NASAWebb will reveal new details of this complex region.

Credit: ESA/NASA/JPL-Caltech/N. Billot (IRAM).

node.text:
This #AsteroidDay, we'd like to recognize someone who just got an asteroid named after her!

[1] Dr. Stefanie Milam is our Deputy Project Scientist for Planetary Science. In her role, she is involved in the amazing science Webb will do observing our own Solar System — everything from planets such as Uranus and Neptune to small bodies such as asteroids and comets.

[2] A grainy close-up, black-and-white view of asteroid 40706 Milam. This image is an overlay of two shots of the same area of the sky. There are two red square boxes around two white dots. The white dots represent that the asteroid has moved across the sky over time.

[3] This is the orbital path of 40706 Milam. As you can see in this image, the asteroid's orbit is beyond that of Mars, within the asteroid belt in between Mars and Jupiter.

node.text:
Oh snap! It’s #NationalCameraDay 📷

Don't blink: We're spotlighting the different cameras that will be helping Webb uncover mysteries of our universe. Webb is a cosmic heat seeker that will detect invisible infrared light, unlike our cell phone cameras, which photograph visible light. The cameras on Webb's NIRCam [image 1] and NIRISS [image 2] instruments will both see in the near-infrared range, while its MIRI instrument [image 3] will take images in the mid-infrared range.

You may have seen far-infrared "heat" cameras at your local museum. These cameras tend to be low-resolution and usually produce grainy images compared to Webb's near-infrared & mid-infrared cameras. For reference, Webb's NIRCam features detectors that each have about 4 million pixels!

Learn more about Webb's detectors at the link in our bio.

Image Credits: [1] Lockheed Martin [2] NASA/Chris Gunn [3] Science and Technology Facilities Council

node.text:
Scientists will use #NASAWebb as an incredible time machine to study six of the most far-flung and luminous quasars—very bright, distant and active supermassive black holes—along with their host galaxies to learn about conditions in the early universe.

What role did quasars play in galaxy evolution during these early times? What can they tell us about the gas between those galaxies? Explore how Webb will view objects as they appeared billions of years ago. Read more at the link in our bio.

Image: This is an artist's concept of a galaxy with a brilliant quasar at its center. A quasar is a very bright, distant and active supermassive black hole that is millions to billions of times the mass of the Sun. Among the brightest objects in the universe, a quasar’s light outshines that of all the stars in its host galaxy combined. Quasars feed on infalling matter and unleash torrents of winds and radiation, shaping the galaxies in which they reside. Using the unique capabilities of Webb, scientists will study six of the most distant and luminous quasars in the universe.
Credits: NASA, ESA and J. Olmsted (STScI)

node.text:
What a pretty galaxy!

This image of NGC 300 was taken in infrared light by the Spitzer Space Telescope. A blue haze marks the greatest concentration of stars, while red highlights the dusty spiral arms.

Astronomers plan to use the James Webb Space Telescope to observe those dusty star-forming regions and pinpoint young star clusters within them.

Credit: NASA/JPL-Caltech/G. Helou (Caltech).

How's this for #NationalSelfieDay? 🤳

Back in 2016, our Senior Project Scientist and Nobel Prize laureate John Mather took a selfie in front of the James Webb Space Telescope in the @NASAGoddard cleanroom. You can see several of our team members reflected in the golden sheen of the iconic primary mirror.

Want to take your own picture with Webb? Check out our virtual backgrounds at the link in our bio!

Image Credit: David Friedlander
